From f6a96fb0969c21af19c6fbe0cc63540f9d5ff3a7 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Robin Jarry <rjarry@redhat.com>
Date: Thu, 5 Feb 2026 10:06:33 +0100
Subject: [PATCH dpdk] graph: add stream enqueue API for batch processing

Introduce a new enqueue API family for graph node process functions:
rte_node_next_stream_enqueue(), _x1, _x2, and _x4.

These functions maintain a small cache of destination streams (up to 4
edges) in the node's fast-path cache line. Objects are written directly
into destination node streams, keeping them cache-hot across interleaved
traffic patterns.

The first edge used is handled lazily: objects stay in node->objs[]
without copying. If all objects go to the same edge (common case),
rte_node_next_stream_move() is used at flush time for zero-copy pointer
swap. When a second edge appears, the first slot is materialized and
subsequent writes go directly to destination streams.

Preferred edges can be declared statically in the node registration
struct (stream_edges[]) or updated at runtime via the new experimental
rte_node_stream_edges_update() API. When no edges are declared, slots
are assigned dynamically as new edges appear.

Signed-off-by: Robin Jarry <rjarry@redhat.com>
---
